          <div class=3D"blog-post__body">
            <span id=3D"hs_cos_wrapper_post_body" class=3D"hs_cos_wrapper h=
s_cos_wrapper_meta_field hs_cos_wrapper_type_rich_text" style=3D"" data-hs-=
cos-general-type=3D"meta_field" data-hs-cos-type=3D"rich_text"><h4>Yeast Pi=
tching Calculator</h4>
<h5>Have you seen or used our <span style=3D"color: #212529;"><span style=
=3D"font-weight: normal;"><a href=3D"https://www.whitelabs.com/research-dev=
elopment" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">PurePitch<sup>=C2=AE</sup> Nex=
t Generation</a> </span></span>Pouches?&nbsp;</h5>
<p>Do you still have some questions about what is printed on the pouch and =
how much to use? If the recommendations confuse you a little bit, or you ju=
st want to dig into some of the science behind it, keep reading!</p>
<!--more-->
<h4>Same Size, Same Cell Count</h4>
<p>Our <span style=3D"color: #212529;"><span style=3D"font-weight: normal;"=
><a href=3D"https://www.whitelabs.com/research-development" rel=3D"noopener=
" target=3D"_blank">PurePitch<sup>=C2=AE</sup> Next Generation</a></span></=
span>=E2=80=99s <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">modular size</span> fits=
 perfectly with the advancements we have made in <span style=3D"font-weight=
: bold;">precise and consistent cell concentrations.</span> Each <span styl=
e=3D"font-weight: bold;">lot is cultured and harvested with specific specif=
ications</span> to ensure each pouch arrives with a consistent and precise =
cell count. <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">Making all strains and lots =
you=E2=80=99re getting the same amount of cells in each and every pouch!&nb=
sp;</span><br><br>PurePitch Next Generation is designed to <span style=3D"f=
ont-weight: bold;">pitch at 7.5 million cells/mL, a commercially recommende=
d pitching rate for standard ale ranges.</span>&nbsp;</p>
<h5 style=3D"text-align: center;"><a href=3D"https://www.whitelabs.com/rese=
arch-development" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">Learn More About PureP=
itch<sup>=E2=93=87</sup> Next Generation</a></h5>
<h4>Brewing Made EASY</h4>
<p>Our easy recommendations work for most fermentations. We wanted to help =
factor in the cell count math for you. With a <span style=3D"font-weight: b=
old;">modular size</span><span style=3D"font-weight: normal;">, scaling up =
is easy at an industry recommended pitch rate.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: normal;"><img src=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.=
com/hs-fs/hubfs/PurePitch%20Next%20Generation%20Scale%20Up.png?width=3D800&=
amp;height=3D276&amp;name=3DPurePitch%20Next%20Generation%20Scale%20Up.png"=
 width=3D"800" height=3D"276" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"PurePitch Next Genera=
tion Scale Up" style=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 800px; margin=
-left: auto; margin-right: auto; display: block;"></span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">We recommend doubling your pitch rate=
 when starting your fermentation below 61=E2=84=89/16=E2=84=83</span> or <s=
pan style=3D"font-weight: bold;">at a higher gravity of 18P or higher</span=
>.</p>
<p>If your fermentation has both, we recommend <span style=3D"font-weight: =
bold;">tripling your pitch rate</span>. These are due to some important fac=
tors explained below.</p>
<h4>colder temperature affect cell growth</h4>
<p><img src=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Cell%20Growth%20Tempe=
rature.png?width=3D800&amp;height=3D495&amp;name=3DCell%20Growth%20Temperat=
ure.png" width=3D"800" height=3D"495" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Cell Growth T=
emperature" style=3D"height: auto; max-width: 100%; width: 800px; float: le=
ft; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 10px;"></p>
<p><span>The most important reason is that colder temperatures inhibit yeas=
t activity to some extent, resulting in reduced or slower cell growth. </sp=
an><span><span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">Slower cell growth can cause lo=
nger fermentation timelines, varying flavor profiles, and most commonly a s=
tuck fermentation.</span> To prevent this, we recommend pitching more yeast=
 to ensure complete fermentation. This means <span style=3D"font-weight: bo=
ld;">increasing your pitch rate to 12+ million cells/mL</span> versus the s=
tandard 7.5 million cells/mL.</span></p>
<h5 style=3D"text-align: center;"><a href=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.com/tip=
s-from-the-pitch-lagers" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank"><span>Check out=
 our Lager Tips &amp; Tricks</span></a></h5>
<h4><span>Why Pitch More With High-Gravity Brews</span></h4>
<p><span>Higher gravity brews provide a higher stress environment for yeast=
 cells. Not only is the wort viscous and <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;"=
>challenging to reach adequate DO </span>(dissolved oxygen) levels, but hig=
her gravity fermentations also <span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">need the =
healthiest yeast possible to withstand the higher alcohol levels</span>. To=
 overcome this challenge, more yeast is required for robust and reliable fe=
rmentation.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h5 style=3D"text-align: center;"><a href=3D"https://46848968.hs-sites.com/=
news-update-detailid100typenews?__hstc=3D43417466.90bc5486a6bb66001b2eab640=
10458e7.1765432716009.1765432716009.1765432716009.1&amp;__hssc=3D43417466.1=
.1765432716009&amp;__hsfp=3D3519258855" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">=
Check Out Our Research On High Gravity Brewing</a></h5>
<h5 style=3D"text-align: center;"><a href=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.com/tip=
s-from-the-pitch-lagers" rel=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank"><span>Check out=
 our Lager Tips &amp; Tricks</span></a></h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h5><span style=3D"font-weight: bold;">Risk of Underpitching/Overpitching</=
span></h5>
<h6 style=3D"font-size: 1.5rem; color: #212529;"><strong>Underpitching</str=
ong></h6>
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 16px;">
<li aria-level=3D"1"><strong>Underpitching gives more room for yeast cells =
to grow and reproduce, therefore creating more yeast-derived flavor in the =
beer.</strong> This can work well in styles such as wheats, belgians, and s=
aisons.&nbsp;</li>
<li aria-level=3D"1"><strong>Underpitching can also lead to stalled ferment=
ations and inadequate clean-up of =E2=80=9Coff=E2=80=9D flavors in the beer=
 maturation phase</strong></li>
<li aria-level=3D"1">With more yeast growth, there will be<strong> more cel=
l growth leading to mutations such as flocculation characteristics</strong>=
</li>
</ul>
<h6 style=3D"font-size: 1.5rem; color: #212529;"><strong>Overpitching</stro=
ng></h6>
<ul style=3D"color: #212529; font-size: 16px;">
<li aria-level=3D"1"><strong>Overpitching leads to less cell growth and les=
s yeast-derived flavor</strong></li>
<li aria-level=3D"1">Overpitching can also <strong>lead to sluggish ferment=
ations over multiple generations</strong>, as with less cell growth means a=
n older yeast cell&nbsp;generation for subsequent batches.
<ul>
<li aria-level=3D"1">=E2=80=8B<em>See the graph below as fermentation speed=
 degrades through subsequent batches&nbsp;with different pitch rates</em></=
li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h4><em><img src=3D"https://blog.whitelabs.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Inoculation%20Pi=
tch%20Rates%20Multiple%20Generations.png?width=3D800&amp;height=3D495&amp;n=
ame=3DInoculation%20Pitch%20Rates%20Multiple%20Generations.png" width=3D"80=
